author: Sihan Goi
text:
Came here for a morning workout. Reached around 7am and there were already people working out, but not too many. The place is quite small - one of the smallest AF I've been too. However, there's ample free weight equipment. 1 PL platform, 2 half racks (facing each other so can get squeezy if 1 or both wish to bench), 1 full rack, 4 barbells (2 hybrid bars, 1 Rogue 45lbs PL bar, and 1 WL bar. The bars spin fine, though I didn't check the Rogue bar. The platform is quite bouncy, so it was not ideal for WL. There's also a hex bar and an EZ bar, 5-20kg rubberised plates (not really bumpers) for the platform, and 1.25-20kg rubberised plates for the racks. Out of the free weights area, there are dumbbells up to at least 44kg (forgot to check), cable machines (very few plate loaded ones though), and the usual cardio machines. Facilities wise, there are pigeonholes and lockers, and 3-4 bathrooms (shower and toilet).

The gym wasn't staffed when I was there, though someone (presumably a PT) came in at around 9am and did a bit of housekeeping before his client. The gym looks generally quite old (both the equipment and the facilities), but still serviceable. Would be better with a regular platform and bumper plates though.

author: beta uprising
text: It used to be a decent gym where members from different disciplines of fitness could workout with the healthy amount of equipment that was provided. As of late, the amount of rogue power bars has been reduced to 1 from the initial 2 which made it inconvenient to train during peak hours as members have to wait a longer time, sharing that 1 bar. This is concerning as some members would resort to using the commercial bars which are older and have lower tensile strength compared to the power bars and when loaded with a lot of plates, it is whippier and a lot more unstable. I hope this gym is able to revert back to the former number of equipments it had to create a safer and accommodating environment for everyone especially when they have an increasing number of users who lifts heavy.

author: Abdul Fattah
text:
This gym used to be a good place to work out, with enough equipment for everyone, no matter what kind of training you were into. But lately, they cut down the number of good-quality power bars from two to just one. Now, during busy times, you have to wait longer to use it, which is really annoying.

Even worse, some people have started using the older, cheaper bars when they can‚Äôt get the good one. Those older bars bend more when loaded with heavy weights, making them shaky and less safe. With more and more people lifting heavy here, I really hope the gym brings back the extra power bar so everyone can train safely and without hassle.

author: Khin Myat Noe Phyu
text:
Please do not sign up to this gym at all cost. Consider other branches to sign up instead!! We have been members for 2 years in here and at first the service and staff were very nice. After a few months in, all the old staff are not around anymore and new staffs are very rude and  unprofessional. Let me break down scenarios and I will tell you why you should not sign up here:
1. You cannot freeze your membership so easily even though you explain them your personal scenarios
2. When you request them to freeze for overseas travel, they can only freeze based on your Airticket booking reference only. For example, we requested to freeze for one month because we will be on overseas for 2 weeks and when we came back is a CNY period so we are sure that we won‚Äôt be able to commit during that period and request for one month, instead the lady is very mean and she told us ‚Äúoh we can only do based on your tickets‚Äù. The attitude is very bad and there is no customer service management skills at all.
3. I was hopping on a teams call on their available desk outside, the women approached me and said that ‚Äúare you working here‚Äù? ‚ÄúIf you are not working here, you cannot sit here at all‚Äù. I even had to ask her if she ask me to change the chair instead. But clearly she ask me to get out. I don‚Äôt understand the fact that I am a member of the gym and I was just waiting my husband for his gym session while working and is not like I am not authorised or never pay and came in for free. She could have asked me more professionally and politely. There are so many ways to say it nicely but she chose to be rude instead.

We have been to so many AF branches before and this is the worst ever! Most of the AF normally got a table and chair and I have seen so many people sitting and working there. Even in this gym, if you don‚Äôt believe me come and see at the night time, there are so many people just chilling there. To be honest, this scenario happens before their office hours which is before 1pm and I am not disturbing or abusing their facilities at all. I am just sitting there to do my job while hopping on a teams call. It is around 10am in the morning and very disappointing to face this kind of thing. I was on the video and I immediately moved from the table once she said it, it was a very disturbing thing for me especially when you are on your work call. She could have handled in a better way and communicate politely but she chose a mean act.

Please think properly before you sign up to this gym. For us, even though we know that their service is getting bad, we are still okay with going there as we have been a member for so long and it is near to our home and my hubby prefers conveniency. But after this incident, we are not gonna be putting this as our home gym anymore.

text:
Im a home member from Rivervale Mall AF. I am writing to express my concern regarding the recent introduction of a $20 fee for using the BIA (Bioelectrical Impedance Analysis) machine at the office. Never have I experienced this before.

I am extremely frustrated by the sudden introduction of a $20 fee for using the BIA machine, especially given that I pay $99 per month as part of my office wellness package. When I signed up for this service, I was under the assumption that all wellness amenities, including the BIA machine, were included as part of the package.

The introduction of this unexpected charge is completely unreasonable and feels like a bait-and-switch tactic. It‚Äôs incredibly disappointing that we are being asked to pay extra for a service that should already be part of the wellness program we‚Äôre paying for.

text:
I‚Äôve been to plenty of AF outlets (even the ones overseas) at this point. So, I mean it respectfully when I say that the gym members here could learn a few things or two on gym etiquette.

Hogging of machines and weights are common. The members are also blatantly smashing the weights on all equipment‚Ä¶ even on the cable machines. I can hear the smashing of the equipment even through my noise-cancelling headphones on max volume.

Other outlets would enforce inconsiderate behaviour like this strictly but you just get the impression that the management here seems to be okay with this.

Call me a boomer-blooded millennial but certain behaviour are ingrained and if the young‚Äôuns are not aware and not informed of good gym etiquette, they will bring those inconsiderate behaviour to other AF outlets.

And when that happens, I‚Äôll be sure to move to other gym chains.

Khan is also a good motivator and he never force me to do things beyond my endurance. I highly recommend him as a good role model as a trainer and friend. Under his guidance and training for 4 months my weight had reduced from 67.9kg to 61.9kg, LDL dropped to 2.9mmol/l and no more knee pain. I used to be overweight, having knee pain, high cholesterol and leading a sedentary lifestyle. Beside having a personal coach I also like the ambience of Anytime Fitness kudos to Khan for your excellence service to your client.

author: Stephanie Quek
text:
Today marks my last training session with Coach Khan, not an easy but fulfilling 1 year journey.

I was huge in size since young and was always on the lookout to try the various fad diets that people rave about but my weight would always yoyo back. In July 2020, I started to exercise more to the extent of jogging 10km x 6 days a week. After 7 months, I hit a plateau despite lots of exercise and low calories intake. My knees suffered from the impact of daily long distance running too. In Feb 2021, I decided to join the gym and look for a PT to learn long-term and sustainable way to lose and maintain my weight.

While using the gym for the first 2 months on my own, I saw how Coach Khan trained his clients with visible results. With his years of experience, he understands the situation I am in and clearly explains the right weight lost journey I should embark on. Thus, I decided to start my PT journey with Coach Khan after talking to him.

Coach Khan is very professional with his training and knows his work at his fingertips. As I have coordination issues and cannot adapt to certain exercises quickly, he will break down the steps accordingly to suit my pace. He will also push me to achieve more reps or heavier lifting that I always think I can‚Äôt do. With resistance and circuit training, I do not need to jog so many times a week; my knees are no longer in constant pain. In addition, Coach Khan had taught me how to track my calories intake and choose the right food. Best of all, I still get to enjoy one favourite meal a week throughout this weight lost journey to keep my sanity. Despite a few rounds of gym closure due to Covid-19, he taught me exercises to do at home and continued to monitor my weekly progress.

Coach Khan has helped me to understand that losing weight and exercise for health is a lifelong journey; there are no short cut ways. Consistency is the key to achieving my goal. I have gained confidence, better health and fitness level to be able to enjoy more outdoor activities with my two teenage sons. I never thought I could lose 20kg to date and hit my target weight at the age of 42, all thanks to Coach Khan‚Äôs guidance. Ladies out there, age is just a number, with the proper training, let us get our health and enjoy more activities in our life.
